PNEUMOCONIOSIS - AUSTRALIA: (QUEENSLAND)
****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 3 Dec 2015
Source: The Guardian [edited]
http://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2015/dec/03/coalminer-with-first-case-of-black-lung-in-60-years-is-still-exposed-to-coal-dust


A coalminer diagnosed with the 1st case of "black lung" in Australia in more than 60 years worked in an underground mine for 6 years after early signs of the disease were missed in a medical examination.

The central Queensland man, 1 of 4 cases this year [2015] of pneumoconiosis, a disease previously thought to have been eradicated from the mining industry, still works in a coal-washing facility where he is exposed to dust, according to a union official.

The shock return of pneumoconiosis among workers in Queensland's underground coalmines, revealed in state parliament this week [week of 1 Dec 2015] by mining minister Anthony Lynham, has blindsided mining companies and prompted the government to threaten closures of mines breaching regulations on dust levels.

Lynham has commissioned an urgent review by Monash University experts of failures in the mining department's health monitoring system, which have left hundreds of thousands of miners' X-rays unchecked.

Professor Malcolm Sim, the head of Monash University's occupational and environmental health research division, told Guardian Australia he would travel to Queensland next [Wed 9 Dec 2015] to confirm terms with the government.

"We're keen to get that review under way as quickly as possible," he said.

The mining department has admitted to a national shortage of experts qualified to detect black lung in X-rays. The Construction, Forestry, Mining and Energy Union (CFMEU) understands there have been no such experts in Queensland for at least 15 years, during which the state's coal industry boomed.

The re-emergence of black lung has been linked to exposure in underground mines, of which there were 13 operating in Queensland in 2013-14, according to the mining department.

Stephen Smyth, the Queensland president of the CFMEU, said the crucial 1st step was to determine how widespread the disease was. Of the 4 people diagnosed with black lung, 3 are believed to be still working in the industry and the other is a retired miner whose exposure to dust came some years ago in Ipswich [Queensland].

Smyth said the union first learned of the disease's re-emergence around May [2015], when the central Queensland miner was diagnosed.

In 2009, the man was given a clean bill of health after 3 medical assessments, including a chest X-ray. A US expert this year [2015] re-examined the 2009 X-ray.

"He picked up within 30 seconds that this [man] actually had the early onset of black lung in 2009, which was not picked up in Queensland," Smyth said.

Mining department documents show that in 1983, the former director of industrial medicine, Mannie Rathus, reviewed 7907 X-rays and of 499 "abnormal" scans, found 75 with signs of black lung, the ABC [Australian Broadcasting Corporation; see http://tinyurl.com/p74ojpt] reported. Rathus's report has never been made public.

Smyth said the union would "welcome any government action" on dust levels in underground mines, which he claimed were routinely in breach of the regulations.

[Byline: Joshua Robertson]

