Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Coal worker's pneumoconiosis (also known as black lung because of the black dust of the coal) is a lung disease that results from breathing in dust from coal, graphite, or man-made carbon over a long period of time.

The risk of getting coal worker's pneumoconiosis depends on how long the workers have been around coal dust. Most people with this disease are older than 50. Smoking does not increase your risk of developing this disease, but it may have an additional harmful effect on the lungs.

Primary symptoms are shortness of breath and coughing.

There is no specific treatment for this disorder. Further exposure to the dust should be avoided. The outcome for the simple form is usually good. It rarely causes disability or death. The complicated form may cause shortness of breath that gets progressively worse.

Workers should wear a protective mask when working around coal, graphite, or man-made carbon. Companies should enforce the maximum permitted dust levels. All workers should avoid smoking.

There seems to be a communication breakdown somewhere. It is unclear if the lung radiographs of the workers were even checked. It does seem clear there is a complaint of not enough radiologists trained to read the radiographs. However, this is the age of telemedicine by the internet. There are radiologists all over the world that read radiographs on a variety of conditions. Electronic radiographs (x-rays) can be sent to any trained radiologist to read the films (no pictures, since they are digital), so a lack of trained radiologists may not be accurate, but it may take many contacts to find a radiologist capable of reading digital radiography regarding pneumoconiosis.

One also has to wonder what the exhaust fans in the mine are doing. Are they regulated? Are the workers wearing protective masks? Is their time in the mine limited? Why would they send a person who has been diagnosed with pneumoconiosis back into the mines? There are likely more questions than answers at the moment. However with 4 of these cases in recent years, it is surprising more aggressive measures are not in place to prevent this condition.

Portions of this comment have been extracted from https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/000130.htm. - Mod.TG

